<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ruppia</i> <i>cirrhosa</i> or <i>Ruppia</i> <i>maritima</i> is the dominant herb forming submerged beds in water with <i>Najas</i> <i>guadalupensis</i>, <i>Potamogeton</i> <i>foliosus</i>, <i>Utricularia</i> <i>macrorhiza</i> and <i>Zannichellia</i> <i>palustris</i>. Emergent plants may be present at low cover, including <i>Myriophyllum</i> spp. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 0.2 m, cover is open to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ruppia cirrhosa</i> or <i>R. maritima</i> > 50% relative cover (Odion et al. 1992a).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Seasonally or permanently flooded brackish marshes, channels, ponds, rivers, coastal wetlands; low-lying basins of high evaporation and infrequent inputs of freshwater into alkaline wetlands. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Ruppia cirrhosa</i> and <i>R. maritima</i> as OBL plants. </div>
</div>

        
