<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ruppia cirrhosa </i>and <i>R. maritima </i>are submersed aquatic plants found in alkaline or saline water in ditches, lakes, ponds, and streams across most of the northern hemisphere and some areas of the southern hemisphere<i>. R. maritima </i>grows best in water with a salinity of 10 parts per thousand or more, but tolerates a wider range between 6 and 20 parts per thousand. The stems are 10-75 cm long, threadlike, and rise from creeping rhizomes; leaves are opposite, grasslike, and sheath the stem at the base. Seeds are small and are borne on slender, stalked clusters (USDA-NRCS 2005). Some botanists consider <i>R. maritima </i>and <i>R. cirrhosa </i>to be a single variable species, with most differences in appearance related to habitat conditions. <br/>
<br/>
Stands occur scattered across California in wetlands that are seasonally or permanently flooded. Seasonal flooding and drying appear to drive stand distribution and abundance, many occurring in coastal lagoons whose shores dry and desiccate by late summer evaporation. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
