    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ab, Af, Ah). <i>Ruppia cirrhosa</i> grows in seasonally impounded waters at Soda Lake and San Antonio Creek Estuary (Botkin et al. 1988, Grewell et al. 2007). <i>R. maritima</i> occurs at Elkhorn Slough, at the mouth of the Salinas River (Matthews 1997), and around San Francisco Bay (Baye et al. 2000) in hyper-saline tidal marsh pans.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Cc). <i>R. cirrhosa</i> grows around the shores of Salton Sea.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Al, Ar, At). <i>R. cirrhosa</i> occurs at Los Banos Wildlife Refuge; <i>R. maritima</i> occurs at San Luis Wildlife Refuge and is dominant in managed marshes around Kesterson Reservoir in the San Joaquin Valley (Schuler et al. 1990).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ae). Both <i>Ruppia</i> species exist in Death Valley and at Little and Owens lakes (DeDecker 1984).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Di). Stands of <i>R. cirrhosa</i> occur at Fish Slough (Odion et al. 1992a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa, Ac-e, Al). <i>R. maritima</i> grows in the salt marshes at the Lake Earl Wildlife Area in Del Norte Co. It occurs around Humboldt Bay, around Stone Lagoon, and at the mouth of the Eel River; <i>R. cirrhosa</i> occurs around Big Lagoon in Humboldt Co.; <i>R. maritima</i> occupies the north shores of Richardson and San Pablo bays (Pickart and Barbour 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Bd-e). Both <i>Ruppia</i> species grow along the shores of Borax Lake, and <i>R. cirrhosa</i> occurs along the shores of Clear and Lower lakes in Lake Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bb, Bd, Bf-g, Bj). <i>R. cirrhosa</i> grows in the salt marshes, usually with algae, at Malibu Lagoon, San Dieguito Lagoon, Santa Anita estuary, and Ventura River estuary; <i>R. maritima</i> occurs at Agua Hedionda Lagoon, Coal Oil Point Reserve, Devereux Slough, and Otay River, Santa Margarita River, and Ventura River estuaries (Beauchamp 1986, Ferren et al. 1990, 1996, Thorne 1982). <i>R. maritima</i> may occur elsewhere in the section, such as at Devereux Slough (Grewell et al. 2007) and on the Channel Islands (Thorne 1967).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bh). Stands of <i>R. cirrhosa</i> occur at Baldwin Lake (Ferren et al. 1996, Thorne 1982).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Most of the coastal lagoons and estuaries with <i>Ruppia </i>are under protected status. Although stands are rare, they currently appear stable or are increasing. Lagoons with irregular water management and climatic fluctuations may affect stand composition because of changes in the salinity, temperature, and/or timing of flooding. Johnson et al. (2003) discussed shifts from <i>Zostera marina </i>to the more ruderal <i>R. maritima </i>in Mission and San Diego bays during warm periods of El Niño events. In addition, algal blooms compete with and may overtop <i>Ruppia </i>plants. </div>
</div>

    

    

